English Summary

Dangerous Numbers: The Dark Side of Armenias Economic Miracle

Armenias Fiscal Challenges and Their Impact on the Countrys Future

Armenia is facing unprecedented fiscal challenges as tax collections have fallen 7.8% below expectations in early 2024 - the first such decline in two decades. This downturn is particularly concerning because it comes amid seemingly impressive economic growth numbers (12.6% in 2022), revealing a disconnect between headline growth and sustainable economic fundamentals. The growth has been largely driven by temporary factors like Russian capital inflows, gold re-exports, and a potentially unsustainable service sector boom.

The technology sector, once heralded as Armenias ticket to sustainable growth, is showing significant signs of strain. The Ministry of High-Tech Industry has only executed 58.4% of its planned budget, while the sector is experiencing negative growth in recent quarters. Combined with currency appreciation and rising costs in Yerevan, these factors are making neighboring countries like Georgia more attractive to tech companies. The situation calls for more than just tactical adjustments - it requires a comprehensive review of Armenias economic foundations, as the current models limitations become increasingly apparent.
